<h1 id=3D"main-title">How to Run Levene=E2=80=99s Test in SPSS?</h1>
<article id=3D"the-content">
<nav id=3D"breadcrumbs"><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-104" class=3D"=
ezoic-adpicker-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"104"></span>
	<span>By Ruben Geert van den Berg</span>
	<span>under <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/basics">Basics</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/statistics-glossary">Statistics A=
-Z</a> &amp; <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/anova">ANOVA</a></sp=
an>
</nav>

<!--body-->

<p>
<span class=3D"def">Levene=E2=80=99s test examines if 2+ populations all ha=
ve<br>
equal variances on some variable.</span>
</p><!-- End Ezoic - gen_under_page_title - under_page_title --><span id=3D=
"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-901" data-method=3D"placement-service"></span><!-=
- Ezoic - gen_under_page_title - under_page_title -->

<ul>
	<!-- <li><a href=3D"#what-is-it">Levene's test - What Is It?</a></li> -->
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/levenes-test-in-spss/#null-h=
ypothesis">Null Hypothesis</a></li><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-709=
" data-method=3D"ai-placeholders" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><spa=
n data-ez-ph-id=3D"709"></span>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/levenes-test-in-spss/#assump=
tions">Assumptions</a></li>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/levenes-test-in-spss/#spss">=
Levene=E2=80=99s test in SPSS</a></li>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/levenes-test-in-spss/#spss-o=
utput">Output</a></li>
	<li><a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/levenes-test-in-spss/#report=
ing">Reporting</a></li>
</ul>


<h2 id=3D"what-is-it">Levene=E2=80=99s Test - What Is It?</h2>

<p>If we want to compare 2(+) groups on a quantitative variable, we usually=
 want to know if they have equal mean scores. For finding out if that's the=
 case, we often use</p>

<ul>
	<li>an <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/spss-independent-samples-=
t-test/">independent samples t-test</a> for comparing 2 groups<strong></str=
ong> or</li>
	<li>a <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/anova-what-is-it/">one-way=
 ANOVA</a> for comparing 3+ groups<strong></strong>.</li><span id=3D"ezoic-=
pub-ad-placeholder-711" data-method=3D"ai-placeholders" class=3D"ezoic-auto=
insert-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"711"></span>
</ul>

<p>Both tests require the <strong>homogeneity</strong> (of variances) assum=
ption: the population variances of the dependent variable must be equal wit=
hin all groups. However, you don't <em>always</em> need this assumption:</p=
><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-710" data-method=3D"ai-placeholders" =
class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"710"></span><!-=
- End Ezoic - gen_under_first_paragraph - under_first_paragraph --><span id=
=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-909" data-method=3D"placement-service"></span>=
<span data-ez-ph-id=3D"909"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_under_first_paragraph -=
 under_first_paragraph -->

<ul>
	<li>you <em>don't</em> need to meet the homogeneity assumption if the grou=
ps you're comparing have roughly equal sample sizes;</li>
	<li>you <em>do</em> need this assumption if your groups have sharply diffe=
rent sample sizes.</li>
</ul>


<p>Now, we usually don't know our population variances but we <em>do</em> k=
now our sample variances. And if these don't differ too much, then the popu=
lation variances being equal seems credible.</p>

<p>But how do we know if our sample variances differ =E2=80=9Ctoo much=E2=
=80=9D? Well,  <strong>Levene=E2=80=99s test</strong> tells us precisely th=
at.</p><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-712" data-method=3D"ai-placehol=
ders" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"712"></sp=
an><!-- End Ezoic - gen_under_second_paragraph - under_second_paragraph -->=
<span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-910" data-method=3D"placement-service"=
></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"910"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_under_second_pa=
ragraph - under_second_paragraph -->


<h2 id=3D"null-hypothesis">Null Hypothesis</h2>

<p>The null hypothesis for Levene=E2=80=99s test is that
<span class=3D"def">the groups we're comparing all have equal population va=
riances.</span>
If this is true, we'll probably find <em>slightly</em> different variances =
in samples from these populations. However, <em>very</em> different sample =
variances suggest that the population variances weren't equal after all. In=
 this case we'll reject the null hypothesis of equal population variances.<=
/p><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-714" data-method=3D"ai-placeholders=
" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"714"></span>


<h2 id=3D"assumptions">Levene=E2=80=99s Test - Assumptions</h2>

<p>Levene=E2=80=99s test basically requires two assumptions:<span id=3D"ezo=
ic-pub-ad-placeholder-109" class=3D"ezoic-adpicker-ad"></span><span data-ez=
-ph-id=3D"109"></span></p>

<ul>
	<li>independent observations and</li><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-=
715" data-method=3D"ai-placeholders" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><=
span data-ez-ph-id=3D"715"></span>
	<li>the test variable is quantitative -that is, not nominal or ordinal.</l=
i>
</ul>


<h2>Levene=E2=80=99s Test - Example</h2>

<p>A fitness company wants to know if 2 supplements for stimulating body fa=
t loss actually work. They test 2 supplements (a cortisol blocker and a thy=
roid booster) on 20 people each. An additional 40 people receive a placebo.=
</p><!-- End Ezoic - gen_mid_content - mid_content --><span id=3D"ezoic-pub=
-ad-placeholder-911" data-method=3D"placement-service"></span><span data-ez=
-ph-id=3D"911"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_mid_content - mid_content -->

<p>All 80 participants have body fat measurements at the start of the exper=
iment (week 11) and weeks 14, 17 and 20. This results in <a href=3D"https:/=
/www.spss-tutorials.com/downloads/fatloss-unequal.sav">fatloss-unequal.sav<=
/a>, part of which is shown below.<span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-113"=
 class=3D"ezoic-adpicker-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"113"></span></p>

<span class=3D"img w720">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/levenes-test-spss-variable-v=
iew-720.png" alt=3D"Levene's Test in SPSS - Example Data Variable View">=20
</span>

<p>One approach to these data is comparing body fat percentages over the 3 =
groups (placebo, thyroid, cortisol) for each week separately.<span class=3D=
"expand-inline-comment active" title=3D"Show Remark">*</span><span class=3D=
"inline-comment js">Perhaps a better approach to these data is using a sing=
le mixed ANOVA. Weeks would be the within-subjects factor and supplement wo=
uld be the between-subjects factor. For now, we'll leave it as an exercise =
to the reader to carry this out.</span>=20
This can be done with an <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/anova-wh=
at-is-it/">ANOVA</a> for each of the 4 body fat measurements. However, sinc=
e we've <strong>unequal sample sizes</strong>, we first need to make sure t=
hat our supplement groups have equal variances.</p><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad=
-placeholder-716" data-method=3D"ai-placeholders" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert=
-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"716"></span>


<h2 id=3D"spss">Running Levene=E2=80=99s test in SPSS</h2>

<p>Several <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/spss-what-is-it/">SPSS=
</a> commands contain an option for running Levene=E2=80=99s test. The <str=
ong>easiest way</strong> to go -especially for multiple variables- is the O=
ne-Way ANOVA dialog.<span class=3D"expand-inline-comment active" title=3D"S=
how Remark">*</span><span class=3D"inline-comment js">This dialog was great=
ly improved in SPSS version 27 and now includes measures of <a href=3D"http=
s://www.spss-tutorials.com/effect-size/">effect size</a> such as <a href=3D=
"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/spss-partial-eta-squared/">(partial) eta sq=
uared</a>.</span> So let's navigate to=20
<span class=3D"spss-menu-block">
		<span class=3D"spss-menu"><i>A</i>nalyze</span>=20
		<img class=3D"icon" src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/spss-menu-arrow=
.png" alt=3D"SPSS Menu Arrow">=20
		<span class=3D"spss-menu"><i>C</i>ompare Means</span>=20
		<img class=3D"icon" src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/spss-menu-arrow=
.png" alt=3D"SPSS Menu Arrow">=20
		<span class=3D"spss-menu"><i>O</i>ne-Way ANOVA</span> </span>=20
and fill out the dialog that pops up.
</p><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-717" data-method=3D"ai-placeholder=
s" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"717"></span>=
<!-- End Ezoic - gen_long_content - long_content --><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-a=
d-placeholder-912" data-method=3D"placement-service"></span><span data-ez-p=
h-id=3D"912"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_long_content - long_content -->
=20
<span class=3D"img w720">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/levenes-test-spss-one-way-an=
ova-menu.png" alt=3D"Levene's Test from SPSS One Way ANOVA Menu">=20
</span>=20
=20
<p>As shown below, <img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"icon" src=3D"https://ww=
w.spss-tutorials.com/img/b2.png?ver=3D1"> the Homogeneity of variance test =
under Options refers to Levene=E2=80=99s test.<span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-plac=
eholder-114" class=3D"ezoic-adpicker-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"114"=
></span></p>

<span class=3D"img w720">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/spss-levenes-test-one-way-an=
ova-dialog-homogeneity-of-variances.png?ver=3D1" alt=3D"Levene's Test from =
SPSS One Way ANOVA Dialog">=20
</span>=20
=20
<p>Clicking <span class=3D"spss-button"><i>P</i>aste</span> results in the =
<a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/spss-syntax/">syntax</a> below. L=
et's run it.</p>


<h2>SPSS Levene=E2=80=99s Test Syntax Example</h2>
=20
<div class=3D"code"><strong>*SPSS Levene's test syntax as pasted from Analy=
ze - Compare Means - One-Way ANOVA.<br></strong><br>ONEWAY fat11 fat14 fat1=
7 fat20 BY condition<br>  /STATISTICS DESCRIPTIVES HOMOGENEITY <br>  /MISSI=
NG ANALYSIS.</div><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-102" class=3D"ezoic-=
adpicker-ad"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"102" style=3D"float:none !import=
ant;box-sizing:content-box;margin-right:auto !important;margin-bottom:15px =
!important;display:block !important;min-height:90px;line-height:0px;margin-=
top:15px !important;margin-left:auto !important;text-align:center !importan=
t;min-width:728px;max-width:100% !important;padding:0;"></span><!--class=3D=
'code'-->

<h2 id=3D"spss-output">Output for Levene=E2=80=99s test</h2>

<p>On running our syntax, we get several tables. The second -shown below- i=
s the <strong>Test of Homogeneity of Variances</strong>. This holds the res=
ults of Levene=E2=80=99s test.</p><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-719"=
 data-method=3D"ai-placeholders" class=3D"ezoic-autoinsert-ad"></span><span=
 data-ez-ph-id=3D"719"></span><!-- End Ezoic - gen_longer_content - longer_=
content --><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-913" data-method=3D"placeme=
nt-service"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"913"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_long=
er_content - longer_content -->

<span class=3D"img w720">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/spss-levenes-test-output.png=
" alt=3D"SPSS Levene's Test Output and Interpretation">=20
</span>=20
=20
<p>As a rule of thumb, we conclude that=20
<span class=3D"def"><strong>population variances are <em>not</em> equal if =
=E2=80=9CSig.=E2=80=9D or <em>p</em> &lt; .05</strong>.</span> For the firs=
t 2 variables, <em>p</em> &gt; .05: for fat percentage in weeks 11 and 14 w=
e <em>don't</em> reject the null hypothesis of equal population variances.<=
span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-115" class=3D"ezoic-adpicker-ad"></span=
><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"115"></span></p>

<p>For the last 2 variables, <em>p</em> &lt; .05: for fat percentages in we=
eks 17 and 20, we reject the null hypothesis of equal population variances.=
 So these 2 variables violate the homogeneity of variance assumption needed=
 for an ANOVA.</p>


<h2>Descriptive Statistics Output</h2>

<p>Remember that we don't need equal population variances if we have roughl=
y equal sample sizes. A sound way for evaluating if this holds is inspectin=
g the Descriptives table in our output.</p><!-- End Ezoic - gen_longest_con=
tent - longest_content --><span id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-914" data-me=
thod=3D"placement-service"></span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"914"></span><!-- E=
zoic - gen_longest_content - longest_content -->

<span class=3D"img w720">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/spss-levene-test-unequal-sam=
ple-sizes.png" alt=3D"Sample Sizes Used for ANOVA in Descriptives Table">=
=20
</span>=20
=20
<p>As we see, our ANOVA is based on sample sizes of 40, 20 and 20 for all 4=
 dependent variables. Because they're not (roughly) equal, we <em>do</em> n=
eed the homogeneity of variance assumption but it's not met by 2 variables.=
</p>

<p>In this case, we'll report alternative measures (Welch and Games-Howell)=
 that don't require the homogeneity assumption. How to run and interpret th=
ese is covered in <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/spss-anova-leve=
nes-test-significant/">SPSS ANOVA - Levene=E2=80=99s Test =E2=80=9CSignific=
ant=E2=80=9D</a>.</p>


<h2 id=3D"reporting">Reporting Levene=E2=80=99s test</h2>

<p>Perhaps surprisingly, Levene=E2=80=99s test is technically an ANOVA as w=
e'll explain <a href=3D"https://www.spss-tutorials.com/levenes-test-in-spss=
/#how-does-levenes-test-work">here</a>. We therefore report it like just a =
basic ANOVA too. So we'll write something like
<span class=3D"def">=E2=80=9CLevene=E2=80=99s test showed that the variance=
s for body fat percentage in week 20 were not equal, <em>F</em>(2,77) =3D 4=
.58, <em>p</em> =3D .013.=E2=80=9D</span>
</p><!-- End Ezoic - gen_incontent_5 - incontent_5 --><span id=3D"ezoic-pub=
-ad-placeholder-915" data-method=3D"placement-service"></span><span data-ez=
-ph-id=3D"915"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_incontent_5 - incontent_5 -->


<h2 id=3D"how-does-levenes-test-work">Levene=E2=80=99s Test - How Does It W=
ork?</h2>

<p>Levene=E2=80=99s test works very simply: a larger variance means that -o=
n average- the data values are =E2=80=9Cfurther away=E2=80=9D from their me=
an. The figure below illustrates this: watch the histograms become =E2=80=
=9Cwider=E2=80=9D as the variances increase.</p>

<span class=3D"img w720">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/histograms-similar-means-dif=
ferent-variances-720.png" alt=3D"Variances Shown in Histograms">=20
</span>=20

<p>We therefore compute the absolute differences between all scores and the=
ir (group) means. The means of these <em>absolute</em> differences should b=
e roughly equal over groups. So technically,
<span class=3D"def">Levene=E2=80=99s test is an ANOVA on the absolute diffe=
rence scores.</span>
In other words: we run an ANOVA (on absolute differences) to find out if we=
 can run an ANOVA (on our actual data).</p>

<p>If that confuses you, try running the syntax below. It does exactly what=
 I just explained.</p><!-- End Ezoic - gen_incontent_6 - incontent_6 --><sp=
an id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-916" data-method=3D"placement-service"></=
span><span data-ez-ph-id=3D"916"></span><!-- Ezoic - gen_incontent_6 - inco=
ntent_6 -->


<h2 id=3D"manual-levenes-test">=E2=80=9CManual=E2=80=9D Levene=E2=80=99s Te=
st Syntax</h2>
=20
<div class=3D"code"><strong>*Add group means on fat20 to dataset.<br></stro=
ng><br>aggregate outfile * mode addvariables<br>/break condition<br>/mfat20=
 =3D mean(fat20).<br><br><strong>*Compute absolute differences between fat2=
0 and group means.<br></strong><br>compute adfat20 =3D abs(fat20 - mfat20).=
<br><br><strong>*Run minimal ANOVA on absolute differences. F-test identica=
l to previous Levene's test.<br></strong><br>ONEWAY adfat20 BY condition.</=
div><!--class=3D'code'-->

<h2>Result</h2>
=20
<span class=3D"img w600">=20
    <img src=3D"https://spss-tutorials.com/img/spss-manual-levenes-test-out=
put.png" alt=3D"SPSS Output for Manual Levene's Test">=20
</span>=20

<p>As we see, these ANOVA results are <strong>identical</strong> to Levene=
=E2=80=99s test in the previous output. I hope this clarifies why we report=
 it as an ANOVA as well.</p>

<p>Thanks for reading!</p>






